#### Death of coral reefs

Corals are multicellular animals that are related to anemones and jellyfish.

* There are thousands of different coral species.
* Individual coral animals, called polyps, build external skeletons made of calcium carbonate (similar to limestone).
* Hundreds of polyps make up coral colonies.
* Each polyp sits in its skeleton cup, and has a central mouth surrounded by tentacles with stinging cells on them.

Corals live in a mutually beneficial relationship (symbiosis) with a type of microalgae called **zooxanthellae**.

* **Zoxanthellae** are single-celled dinoflagellate microalgae.
* They are responsible for the brown colour of many corals.
* The bright pinks, greens and blues also seen in coral reefs are produced by fluorescent compounds made by the coral host that protect the zooxanthellae from getting too much sunlight, which can be a problem at the middle of the day on coral reefs in the tropics. Corals and Zoxanthellae have a **symbiosis relationship**.

